        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Takilth SP</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Neverwinter Nights and it's ilk may be the counterbalance for MMORPGs of the future.  While NWN in it's current config is too much of a hog to allow more than 10 or so running in a world at the same time, it is a game that will foster creative world, quest and dungeon-designs on the part of the player-base.  The MMORPG concept has so much going for it if the designers just take it a step or two further and with NWN out there, some of the possibilities may be put up for show.</P><P>As it stands now, EQ is a horribly static world - painfully so.  While the player characters grow and develop, the world stays the same day in and day out - and you end with a top-heavy collection of players with nothing to do and overcompetition for resources.  With some creative design introduced into a game like this players could be re-engaged in the experience to the point where levelling and power-mongering would be relegated more to the background.  Take for instance the possibility that the GMs that patrol the world now looking for violaters of the Play Nice Policy - if they and their team were instead responsible for driving the worlds Mobs and NPCs along an ongoing storyline that develops each day.  I'm not talking about the current GM-Events that are jokes.  I'm talking about everyday interactions, from the low-level to the guild-raid.  It would require the GMs having access to a new toolset along the lines of what NWN provides, but the concept has merit in my book.  Some version of this idea in different scales is an example of what I'd like to see down the line.</P><P>my 2cp</P><P></P><P>Takilth Shadowpath<BR>aka Necrotart<BR>Iksar Warlock of the Final Shedding<BR>proud member of Shining Alliance<BR>Prexus</P><P>Edited by - Takilth SP on 07/16/2002  17:15:55</font></td>
