        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Personaly I like the idea of item decay, but it should be done correctly.  alot of what great swordsmen learned was how not to destoy thier weapons, and how to take care of them.</P><P>for item decay to be plausable you need skills that govern it. If you know how to proprly use a weapon you could assume that you know the basics of it's use and repair.  naturaly you could not take it from shatterd and make it work again, but you would know how it was put to geather, how to fix a wobbly hilt, sharpen the blade, protect it from rust ect.<BR>so knowing how to use a weapon or armor one would assume they do not decay at all under normal useage. using weapons that are out of your skill range would cause item decay, as well as armor out of your usuage would cause it to decay, armor to far from you skill would be unusable.  afterall, some one that has for the first time seen plate armor is going to have a verry hard time putting it on correctly.  (hell how many knights could put on thier own armor?)<BR>Add certain mobs that increase item decay.  sure, you may know how to twist your sword when in a duel with another swordsmen so as not to damage the blade when you connect blade to blade, but how do you poke a dragon through scales without damaging the edge?<BR>Finaly a crafting skill that requiers special tools.  when weapons are damaged to certain degree they are no longer usable/barely usable they would requier a craftsman to fix the items.  this needs to be a player and npc skill.  npc's should charge under normal circumstances.</P><P>effectivly this would mean that the only time you actualy need to stop to repair weapons/armor would be after a raid, or if your a twink.  item decay is a great thing to have, it adds depth to characters and items, yet it does add somthing a bit tedious to look after.  <BR>if you wanted to get technical for PvP you could add weapons desined to break others equipment (spanish sword breaker any one?), but I could really see some one going off the deep end when thier vorpal sword of anus removal gets snaped like a twig by some punks $2 sword breaker.</P><P>The main thing I like to see in games is</P><P>1) compleated content.  I hate it when you work like hell for some quest only to find out XXX item is not in the game.</P><P>2) macro's.  any online game NEEDS macros.  fully customizable.  if you can script an entier battle into a macro, GREAT!  and macros should be able to do just about any function the user can with mouse / keyboard / voice command.</P><P>3) information about the game, IN the game.  example, DAoC's trade skills.  that is the best feature of the game yet.  yet that should be expanded.</P><P>4) alot of people (myself included) have poured alot of $$ into killing brazil to print out maps for nearly every zone in EQ.  please save us this trouble, let the characters map the world for them selves.  let characters add in thier own notes / details for a map.</P><P>5) a basic text editor.  this is one feature I have said should ALWAYS be in a RPG, online offline, or side line, it needs a text editor.  so far the only one I know of that belives me on this is NWN.</P><P>6) a con system that advances with skill.  when you first start out, you think you can kick any things ass.  quickly learning the errors of your ways and how to evaluate and sum up your oponet.</P><P>7) Mobs that ALWAYS give XP / Loot.  I admit, thier is no challange for my to kill a fire bettle any more.  but if I were to work at killing 800 firebeetles it would either take alot of time, or a decent start.  if the base XP for a fire beetle is 5, and I need 256000 xp to gain level 25 as you can easly see I would need to kill 51200 firebeetles to get 25, no simple task.</P><P>8) multiple methods of advancing skill.  thier should be training and skill advancment through use, some skills you can train, others are only learn as you go.  one of the better mud's I played had a great system for skill advancment.  basicaly you had the oposit chance of you skill to advance (all skills were 100), when ever you failed with that skill.  naturaly the better you get naturaly the harder it is ti raise. at skill 5 at pissing, you have a 95% chance to gain a point if you cannot piss, yet at 60 you have a 40% chance to increase if you cannot piss. at 95, you are king of the pissing contest, but hardly ever find a time you cannot piss, and on the rare occasion you cannot, you only have 5% chance to naturaly raise that skill.<BR>Personaly I like this idea quite a bit for RPG use.  it encourages people to learn multiple skills, and save points to raise what they would like to specilize in.  the down side of this mud was that people could easly become a jack of all trades, so you might want to adjust it so that people always have at best 50% chance to raise a skill on failure. (note a missed melee attack was not considered a failure, a miss aginst a base AC was considred, or in D&D tearms a natural roll of 5 or less).</P><P>9) Mobs that drop loot correctly.  why when you kill a guard in full plate you some times get a shield?  should you have gotten all but the BP, Helm and Vamb that you crushed killing the guard.  of course some things such as that should be difficult to sell.  seriously what merchant in thier right mind would by bloody and dented armor from thier own city guard . . . . or right, ol ratz on 3rd street . . .</P><P><BR>now if only you could make an MMORPG into an OS, so as to unload that bulky windows crap, and have direct access to the file system.  with an encrypted partition it could quite well cut down on hacking.  would just need to have one hell of an interface . . .</P><P>edited for readablity.</P><P></P><P></P><P><BR><center><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=11832" target="_blank">Bringer of Darkness</a><BR><a href="http://members.cox.net/umbrae/pic.jpg" target="_blank">Signature Pic PG